<DOC><DOCNO> AP880226-0003 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 2342EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Vietnam-China     02-26 0238</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Vietnam-China,0246</SECOND><HEAD>Vietnam Says Chinese Troops Landed on Disputed Islands</HEAD><DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Vietnam has accused China of landingtroops on two coral reefs of a South China Sea archipelago claimedby both countries, according to a Vietnamese newspaper report madeavailable Saturday.   The Communist Party newspaper, Nhan Dan, said Chinese militaryforces had landed on Chu Thap and Chau Vien, two coral reefs in theTruong Sa, or Spratly archipelago.   ``The situation in the Truong Sa archipelago and the eastern seaas a whole is becoming dangerously tense due to the Chineseauthorities' brazen violations of Vietnam's territorial sovereigntythere,'' the newspaper said in a front page article Friday.   On Feb. 20, Vietnam charged that four Chinese warships``provoked and obstructed'' operations of its cargo vessels Jan. 31off the Spratly group. Beijing has denied the accusation.   The latest Vietnamese report gave no further details of thealleged Chinese troop landings.   Several countries claim the Spratly group as well as theParacels, an archipelgo called Hoang Sa by the Vietnamese. Largeoil deposits are said to be located in the vicinity.   China stations troops in the Paracels while Vietnam holds a fewislands in the Spratlies. But claims on parts or all of the twochains have also been made by Malaysia, the Philippines and Taiwan.   China and Vietnam fought a bloody border war in 1979 and havesince accused each other of frontier violations.</TEXT></DOC>